nile court records, premiers' papers, memoirs, and oral histories to uncover the ways in which the material workings of the family and the discursive category of 'respectable' citizenship were invested with gendered obligations and Anglo-British identity. Respectable Citizens demonstrates how women and men represented themselves as entitled to make specific claims on the state, shedding new light on the cooperative and conflicting relationships between men and women, parents and children, and citizen and state in 1930s Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aChômeursxConditions socialesx20e sièclexOntario. 0aChômeursxServices auxx20e sièclexOntario. 0aFamiliesxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxOntario. 0aFamilieszOntarioxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aFamillexConditions socialesx20e sièclexOntario. 0aFemmesxConditions socialesx20e sièclexOntario. 0aUnemployedxServices forxHistoryx20th centuryxOntario. 0aUnemployedxServices forzOntarioxHistoryy20th century. 0aUnemployedxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxOntario. 0aUnemployedzOntarioxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxOntario. 0aWomenzOntarioxSocial conditionsy20th century. 4aCoursebook. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269741640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442697416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442697416.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE 